Introduction:

The quality of life has significantly improved worldwide over the last two decades due to major breakthroughs in the healthcare and pharmaceutical industries. Diseases that were once deemed fatal have become treatable as a result of new therapeutics and surgical procedures. Consequently, populations across the world are healthier today compared to any period in history. Life expectancy is a measure of the average number of years a person is expected to live based on a variety of factors such as gender, ethnicity, and occupation. This metric is a key indicator of a population’s overall health and typically used as a measure of the quality of life in a country. Based on the research conducted by The World Health Organization (WHO), the world’s life expectancy has increased from 66.2 years to 73.2 years since 2000, which is a 10% increase averaged amongst all people from different parts of the world. Most countries hold confidence and refer to the data collected by The World Health Organization (WHO), which has served as the global leader regarding this topic for the last 80 years. Not only does life expectancy provide information about the longevity of a population, it also gives lawmakers the necessary information to create informed healthcare policies that actually benefit their citizens. For example, a country with a high life expectancy might be able to reallocate resources away from healthcare and towards something like education. In contrast, a country with a low life expectancy would benefit from further investment in healthcare and new medical technology.

Another important national health metric that is measured by the WHO is the Human Development Index (HDI). In short, the HDI is a complex statistic, created in 1990, that measures a country’s development in three overarching categories: health, education, and income. Analysis of the data from the World Health Organization prompted us to develop our first question: How accurately can we predict Human Development Index (HDI) by combining models for predicting Life Expectancy and GDP? A logical hypothesis is that a country with a higher life expectancy and higher GDP per capita would have a higher HDI. However, we wanted to examine this question in detail by considering the weight of the variables that best predict Life Expectancy and GDP.

We also wanted to investigate which variables most heavily impact the development status of countries as the WHO lists the development status of every country they monitor. In the dataset, a country is marked as either “developed” or “developing”. It is easy to imagine the things that make a country developed: political stability, high resource accessibility, and a strong international reputation. However, according to the United Nations Statistical Division, there is no actual established criteria that defines a “developed” nation nor distinguishes the categorical designation of a “developing” nation. This leads us to our second overarching question: How accurately can a country’s development status be predicted based on other variables in the dataset? We wanted to analyze the cutoff criteria between developed and developing nations through answering this question. We know a high life expectancy is a necessary component, but how high must it be? How wealthy must the nation be? How well-educated? These answers can be achieved by creating models that incorporate both the health-related and money-related variables. Ultimately, the results of analyzing these questions will allow us to determine the weight of life expectancy on a “developed” designation as a whole, or discover if other variables should be considered to define status.

While many countries have access to ample resources, there is still a significant discrepancy in access to resources throughout the world. The investigation of our two questions is important to highlight possible ways for countries to assess and improve quality of life. This type of assessment would allow governments around the world to reevaluate their policies and allocate resources accordingly. The ultimate purpose of our analysis is to promote better understanding of what measurable statistics can define a standard of living in the context of a country’s development progression and eventually bridge the life expectancy gap across the world.

Results

Question 1:

To answer our first question - How accurately can we predict Human Development Index (HDI) by using combined models for predicting Life Expectancy and GDP - multiple models were required to figure out how to best predict life expectancy and GDP per capita data. Our first step to answering this question was to find the best model for both life expectancy and GDP per capita. We first removed the HDI variable from our dataset because ultimately we were trying to predict HDI, therefore, it didn’t make sense to include it in our intermediate life expectancy and GDP models. We also decided to remove the Country variable as its potential complications outweighed any benefits it may have added to the prediction accuracy. From there, we created five models for both GDP and Life Expectancy with the intention of selecting the best one for each variable.

The five models we chose to include were an empty model, a full model using all variables except the two discussed above, and three full models, which utilized a penalized maximum likelihood method via the glmnet function from the glmnet package. These three models included single, 2-way, and 3-way interactions between variables respectively. It was important for us to use the glmnet function because it eliminates unnecessary variables by optimizing the model and converging unnecessary variables’ coefficients to 0 (and thus not including them in the final model). This allowed us to create the simplest version of each model. Additionally, we decided to include both the 2-way and 3-way interactions between variables because of the nature of our dataset. Our dataset includes many variables that are inherently dependent on one another so we thought it would be naive of us to view them all as independent in our modeling. When finding predictions for each of our models, we utilized a 10 k-fold cross-validation method to create accurate predictions and utilize our entire dataset. The table shown below lists the results from each model and ranks them based on the Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE):

As shown above, the full model with 3-way interactions proved to be the best performing model for both life expectancy and GDP. This is likely due to our variables being heavily dependent on one another. From there, we standardized the data so that all of the variables were in the same units, which allowed us to better understand the role that individual variables play in the model as a whole. We then reproduced the best performing model for both GDP and Life Expectancy on the standardized data and sought to combine them into a model we refer to as the Combined Model. To do this, we took an average of the coefficients from the Life Expectancy model and the GDP model and created the new model. In order to analyze our new combined model, we needed to create a model that was designed to predict HDI. To do this, we added the HDI variable back into the dataset and only included variables which were relevant to our combined model. From there, we used the glmnet function to create the model we would compare to our combined model. We found that the combined GDP and Life Expectancy Model was not a good predictor for Human Development Index, with a RMSE of 1.077 scaled units.

Given that there were 157 variables in our three-way interaction combined model, we decided to take a more straightforward approach by using this same combining technique but with a simple linear regression model. Again, we found the coefficients from both the GDP model and the Life Expectancy model and took an average between the two of them to calculate the coefficients for our combined models. Question 2

In answering our second question - How accurately can a country’s development status be predicted based on the other variables in the dataset? - we decided to look at it from different lenses. Using the many variables included in our dataset, we were able to assemble four different models to predict the development status of a country. For each model, we chose a central focus and selected the variables that would be used to predict the development status. Our first model includes all the variables from the dataset to establish a base model to refer back to and use as a baseline comparison. This model was found to have a predicted error of 6.73% and showed high accuracy in the status prediction of developing countries against developed. The second model was a full model with two-way interactions taken into consideration. Including two-way interactions resulted in slight improvement in accuracy with an overall prediction error of 5.22% but a slight decrease in the prediction of developed countries specifically. After constructing a base model and two-way interaction model, our next two models were meant to focus on variables related to healthcare and the economic state of the country respectively. Adult mortality, infant deaths, alcohol, hepatitis b, measles, bmi, under five deaths, polio, diphtheria, hiv/aids, underweight ages 5-9, and underweight ages 10-19 were all variables we considered to be related to healthcare and thus, used in model three. The final model, which focused on the economic-related variables utilized percentage expenditure, total expenditure, and gdp to examine the economic state and utilize it to predict the country’s development status. Models 1, 2, and 3 all had very similar prediction error results, however, model 4 demonstrated a significant decrease in prediction accuracy. Below, the table summarizes each model and the predicted vs actual error when applied to our dataset:

Status Predicted Error Actual Error
Model 1 - full model 0.0673135 0.0667071
Model 2 - full model + two way interactions 0.0521528 0.0327471
Model 3 - health related variables 0.0673135 0.0661007
Model 4 - economic related variables 0.1267435 0.1255306

Additionally, we decided to look into whether there is a difference in prediction errors between developed and developing countries. We ran 10 k-fold cross validation to gather predictions and divided predictions into two groups based on their development status. Next, we calculated the proportion of correct predictions for each development status in order to plot prediction errors. Wen repeated the process for all four models and used facet_wrap to put the four plots next to each other for comparison. The plot below suggests that prediction errors for developed countries are significantly higher compared to developing countries for all four models. We believe that the difference in prediction error is due to the large difference in sample sizes for developed and developing countries (242 and 1407 observations respectively). Developing countries are expected to have lower prediction errors as a result of having a larger sample size than the developed countries.

Finally, we decided to compare prediction errors among the four models as shown in the plot above to examine the ability to predict development status using different sets of predictors. Using the full model as the benchmark, we observed that adding two-way interaction improved the model and reduced prediction errors regardless of the development status. Comparing model 1 (the base model) against model 3, we observed that using only health-related variables as predictors did not have a significant impact on reducing prediction errors. However, model 4, using only money-related variables as predictors, displayed the most interesting plot that was worth further investigation. Compared to the benchmark, model 4 significantly increased prediction errors for developed countries while decreasing prediction errors for developing countries. This indicates that money-related variables are good predictors for developing countries but not so much for developed countries. We believe this observation can be explained by the differences between developing and developed countries. While economic consideration is a significant factor, it is not the only factor important to assessing a country’s development status. Therefore, money-related variables are good at accurately predicting developing countries because limited economic resources indicate the country is still developing in most cases. Conversely, ample economic resources and high GDP per capita do not necessarily indicate that a country is considered developed as many other factors, including healthcare and education, need to be considered. This observation further indicates the importance of health factors, including life expectancy, in evaluating the overall development status.

Conclusion:

Our first question explored the predictive value between GDP and Life Expectancy on a country’s Human Development Index. We hypothesized that combining models used to predict GDP and Life Expectancy would create an accurate prediction of HDI. However, that wasn’t the case. Our two versions of combined models (3-way interaction and simple linear regression) produced predictions that hovered around the mean value of HDI - 0 when using standardized variables. This indicates that our combined model didn’t put enough emphasis on crucial variables required to accurately predict HDI. That being said, this is a somewhat expected finding because it shows that Human Development Index is more complex than just combining GDP and Life Expectancy. It is commendable that the Human Development Index recognizes the need for a comprehensive approach to measuring human development, one that takes into account not just economic and health factors, but also education, gender equality, and other social factors that contribute to a high quality of life. Advancing humanity across the globe requires us to look at more complicated and multifaceted metrics rather than simply equating a county’s GDP or Life Expectancy with quality of life.

For our second question, we investigated how well the development status of a country can be predicted by other variables in the dataset. The differences in prediction accuracy when grouping different variables together enabled us to further examine the role they play in assessing the overall development of a country. After constructing four models, each with different sets of variables and comparing prediction errors against one another, we concluded that adding two-way interactions provided the lowest prediction errors and thus, the best model. The most insightful finding, however, was that model 4 - with only economic variables - performed the best at accurately predicting developing countries, while performing the worst at predicting developed countries. Our hypothesis for this observation is that economic growth has diminishing effects on improving a country’s development status. In other words, economic factors alone are not enough for a developing country to become developed. However, having inadequate economic standing automatically disqualifies a country from being eligible for developed status. We believe this insight is crucial for policymakers to understand so that resources can be allocated more efficiently for more holistic policies. As developing countries try to speed up the process as much as possible, economic growth is often a priority for policymakers while drafting policies and making investments. However, it is also important to look into other areas, including life expectancy and education, so that the development process can be more robust and efficient.

Our research project effectively explores the relationship between Life Expectancy, GDP, and the overall development of a country. We were also able to develop a better understanding of how different variables interact with each other in our models. Similar to economic growth, life expectancy alone is not sufficient for a holistic assessment of how developed a country is. The purpose of our project is to promote broader awareness of how important it is for policymakers to think beyond the status quo to create more effective development plans. At the same time, our project can be used as a foundation for further research when more variables are added to the dataset.
